One winter morning a few years ago, in Johannesburg, South Africa, when I drove to work, I found that the city was covered by smog.
I drive by there almost every day, but this time is very unusual, I have never seen such a sight before.
Johannesburg is famous for its distinctive and beautiful skyline, but it was almost invisible that morning.
I soon realized that what I saw was the severe smog caused by air pollution.
The contrast between the beautiful environment that I used to know and the smog-shrouded skyline at this moment is constantly surging in my heart.
I am worried that it is very possible that the once colorful sunset will be swallowed by the gloomy haze.
At that moment, I felt a strong urge to do something, but I didn’t know what to do.
All I know is that I can’t just stand by.
The biggest challenge is that I don’t understand environmental science. Air quality management, or atmospheric chemistry.
I am a computer engineer, and I am pretty sure that I cannot solve the problem of air pollution by coding.
(Laughter) In what capacity will I solve this problem?
I’m just a small civic.
In the next few years, I learned a very important lesson. If we want to achieve a better future, we should all keep this lesson in mind.
Even if you are not an expert in a particular field, your professional skills may contain solutions to problems in that field.
Sometimes, your unique perspective can inspire unconventional thinking and influence the situation, but you need to be bold to try.
Only then can you know the result.
What I knew at the time was that if I wanted to try to change, I had to know enough about pollution first, so I became a student again.
I did some basic research and quickly learned that air pollution is the biggest environmental health risk in the world.
Data from the World Health Organization show that in 2012, almost 14% of deaths worldwide were caused by air pollution at home and surrounding areas, especially in low- and middle-income countries.
The annual death rate caused by air pollution is higher than that of malaria and AIDS.
In Africa, premature deaths caused by unsafe sanitary conditions, or deaths caused by children’s malnutrition, pale in the face of air pollution. At the same time, it also brings huge economic costs: According to statistics from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, 2013 Expenditures on related parties exceeded US$400 billion in 2015.
In my work, I explore the cutting-edge achievements of artificial intelligence, including the symbiotic relationship between humans and machines, to find a useful foothold and help us make better decisions.
