Many people think that driving is something that only those who can see can do.
Blind people want to drive a car safely and alone until now, it has also been considered an impossible task.
Hello everyone, my name is Dennis Hong. We have built a car designed for people with visual impairments for the freedom and independence of the blind.
Before I talk about this car for the blind, let me briefly talk about another project I have done called the US Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency Urban Challenge.
This is about making a mechanical car that can drive by itself.
You press the start button, no longer touch anything, it can also reach its destination completely automatically.
In the 2007 Challenge, our team won $500,000 and won the third place in the competition.
Around that time, the National Association of the Blind, or the Association for the Blind, challenged the design team about who could design a car that allowed blind people to drive independently and safely.
We think we have to try it, because we think, hey, where is this going to be difficult.
We already have an autonomous car.
We just need to let the blind drive inside, and that’s not the end, right?
(Laughter) But we were wrong and unreliable.
What the Blind Association wants is not a car that can carry blind people around, but a car that blind people can actively make choices and drive.
So we had to give up all our original things and start from scratch.
To test this crazy idea, we designed a prototype of a small dune truck to test its feasibility.
In the summer of 2009, we invited many blind young people across the country and gave them a chance to take this car for a ride.
This is definitely a cool experience.
But the problem with this car is that its design can only allow blind people to drive in a very limited environment, like a closed parking lot - even on small roads built with red traffic cones.
So with this success, we decided to take an important next step, to build a real car that can drive on real roads.
How does it work?
Well, this is a relatively complex system, but let me explain it to simplify it.
We have three stages.
We have a sensing phase, a calculation phase and a non-visual interface.
The driver is obviously invisible, so the system must be able to perceive the surrounding environment and collect data for the driver.
At this point, we use the initial metering element.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration - just like the human ear, the inner ear.
I combined this information with the global positioning system to predict the location of the vehicle.
We also use two cameras to detect the path of the vehicle.
We also use three laser rangefinders.
The laser scans the environment to detect obstacles-vehicles passing by from the front and rear at the same time, any obstacles breaking into the road, and any obstacles around the vehicle.
All the massive amounts of information are then aggregated into the computer, and the computer will do two things.
First, one thing is to process information to understand the surrounding environment - which are driving paths and which are obstacles - and transform this information to the driver.
This system is also very intelligent and can calculate the safest driving path.
We can also issue instructions on how to operate the vehicle’s operating procedures.
But the question is: How can we transmit information and instructions to the blind person quickly and accurately to ensure that he can drive?
To this end, we have designed many different non-visual user interface technologies.
The original three-dimensional flat sound system, vibrating vests, voice-activated gears, leg straps, and even shoes that put pressure on the feet.
But today we are talking about three of these non-visual user interface technologies.
The first interface is called the driving handle.
This is a pair of gloves. It has vibration elements on the knuckles, so you can transmit instructions on how to drive - direction and amplitude.
Another device is called a velocity shock belt.
This car chair--actually, this is a massage chair.
We took it apart, and we reorganized the vibration elements of different modes. We let them transmit speed information, as well as instructions on how to use the accelerator and brake.
Here, you can see how the computer understands the surrounding environment. Because you can’t see the vibration, we actually installed a red LED on the driver so he can see what is happening.
This is the sensed data, which is transferred from the sensor to the computer.
So these two devices, the steering handle and the speed shock belt, are very effective.
But the problem is that these are instruction hinting devices.
So this is not freedom in the true sense, right?
The computer tells you how to drive - turn left, turn right, accelerate, brake.
I call this the co-pilot problem.
So we are avoiding instruction suggesting devices and focusing more on information devices.
A typical example of such a non-visual information interface is called an empty map.
Think of this as a display for the blind.
This is a small table top with many holes on it, compressed air is excluded from it, so it can be described as a picture.
So even if you are blind and you put your hand on it, you can sense the path and obstacles.
In fact, you can also change the frequency and possibly temperature released in the air.
This is actually a multi-dimensional user interface.
Here, you can see the cameras on the left and right and how the computer parses and sends this information to the empty image.
In this way, we are showing a simulation program where a blind person is driving with an empty chart.
This program is very helpful for training blind drivers and quickly testing different theories in terms of different types of non-visual user interfaces.
This is basically how it works.
But this car is a model car, and it will not go on the road unless it is proven to be as safe as today’s car, or safer.
I really believe this will happen.
But is society, can they accept this radical idea?
How will we deal with insurance?
How will we issue a driver’s license?
